What are Modules?

A module is simply a JavaScript file.

Instead of writing all your code in one file:

script.js
├── Functions
├── Variables
├── Classes
├── Objects
├── 1000+ lines

You can split it into multiple files:

project/
│
├── math.js
├── user.js
├── product.js
├── app.js

This makes your code:

✅ Cleaner
✅ Easier to maintain
✅ Reusable
✅ Better organized
Why Use Modules?

Imagine an e-commerce application.

Instead of one huge file:

app.js

Create separate modules:

math.js
user.js
product.js
payment.js
app.js

Each file has a specific responsibility.

Creating a Module
math.js
export function add(a, b) {
    return a + b;
}

export function subtract(a, b) {
    return a - b;
}

Here, export makes the functions available to other files.

Named Import
app.js
import { add, subtract } from "./math.js";

console.log(add(10, 20));
console.log(subtract(30, 10));
Output
30
20
Exporting Variables
config.js
export const company = "OpenAI";

export const year = 2026;
app.js
import { company, year } from "./config.js";

console.log(company);
console.log(year);

Output

OpenAI
2026
Exporting Multiple Items
export const PI = 3.14;

export function square(num) {
    return num * num;
}

export let city = "Coimbatore";

Import:

import { PI, square, city } from "./math.js";
Default Export ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

A file can have only one default export.

user.js
export default function greet() {

    console.log("Hello!");

}

Import:

import greet from "./user.js";

greet();

Output

Hello!

Notice:

No {} with default import.

Default Export with Variables
const company = "OpenAI";

export default company;

Import:

import company from "./company.js";

console.log(company);
Named Export vs Default Export
Named Export	Default Export
export function add(){}	export default function(){}
Use {} while importing	No {}
Multiple allowed	Only one per file
Import Alias

Suppose:

export function add(a, b) {

    return a + b;

}

Import with another name:

import { add as sum } from "./math.js";

console.log(sum(5, 10));

Output

15
Import Everything

Instead of importing each function separately:

import * as math from "./math.js";

console.log(math.add(10, 20));
console.log(math.subtract(20, 10));

Output

30
10
Export at the Bottom

Instead of:

export function add() {}

export function sub() {}

You can write:

function add(a, b) {
    return a + b;
}

function sub(a, b) {
    return a - b;
}

export { add, sub };
Combining Default and Named Exports
calculator.js
export const PI = 3.14;

export function square(x) {
    return x * x;
}

export default function add(a, b) {
    return a + b;
}

Import:

import add, { PI, square } from "./calculator.js";

console.log(add(10, 20));
console.log(PI);
console.log(square(5));

Output

30
3.14
25
Using Modules in HTML
<script type="module" src="app.js"></script>

Without type="module", import and export will not work.

